From: Kamil Bienkiewicz <perceivalpercy@gmail.com>
Date: Sun, 17 May 2026 11:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] net: pcs: qcom-ipq9574: Tolerate MII clock enable failure

Phylink calls pcs_enable BEFORE pcs_config. clk_prepare_enable on the
NSSCC uniphy_port_rx/tx_clk branches polls hardware ack of the clock
branch. On IPQ5332, the underlying SerDes hasn't been configured yet
when pcs_enable runs, so the upstream RX clock isn't producing pulses
and the NSSCC branch poll times out → -ETIMEDOUT.

This blocks pcs_enable but phylink ignores the return value, so link
"comes up" via fixed-link state — but the downstream MII clock gate
never actually opens. For traffic to flow we need the gate open after
SerDes is up.

Workaround: in pcs_enable, log clk_prepare_enable failures and return
0 anyway. clk_prepare reference counting on the failed enable is
slightly off but the deferred enable in pcs_link_up (if added) would
recover. For now this just gets us past the pcs_enable wall.

Signed-off-by: Kamil Bienkiewicz <perceivalpercy@gmail.com>
---
--- a/drivers/net/pcs/pcs-qcom-ipq9574.c
+++ b/drivers/net/pcs/pcs-qcom-ipq9574.c
@@ -643,8 +643,8 @@ static int ipq_pcs_enable(struct phylink

 	ret = clk_prepare_enable(qpcs_mii->rx_clk);
 	if (ret) {
-		dev_err(qpcs->dev, "Failed to enable MII %d RX clock\n", index);
-		return ret;
+		dev_warn(qpcs->dev, "Failed to enable MII %d RX clock (%d) — continuing\n", index, ret);
+		ret = 0;
 	}

 	ret = clk_prepare_enable(qpcs_mii->tx_clk);
@@ -653,8 +653,8 @@ static int ipq_pcs_enable(struct phylink
 		 * the state back for this error. So, we only report the error
 		 * and do not disable the clocks.
 		 */
-		dev_err(qpcs->dev, "Failed to enable MII %d TX clock\n", index);
-		return ret;
+		dev_warn(qpcs->dev, "Failed to enable MII %d TX clock (%d) — continuing\n", index, ret);
+		ret = 0;
 	}

 	return 0;
